ss with an interface to exercise that interface branch. However, it seems the class$ call only executes if `class$javax$...` is null, meaning if it has a non-null static field from any prior calls, that won't be covered. To address coverage, I could create a fresh copy of the library class through a custom classloader, but that's quite complex. Using Java serialization doesn't seem to be the right fit either.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Inspecting dynamic access coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI need to look into the TCK runner and see if it can provide dynamic access coverage through the JaCoCo report using the call tree stack. If a class is loaded by a custom loader with the same name, that might count. However, native images can't load new classes from a JAR. I wonder if I could include local native-image metadata to enforce runtime initialization or register `SimpleTagSupport` for that purpose. I might need to add test resources with `--initialize-at-run-time=javax.servlet.jsp.tagext.SimpleTagSupport`.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_bpo6feANVEKWJg6Bi4BX6iN9|fc_0ce04a3ba3fd22ec0169f5491a4a4081a0bf4f8381325eb56c\", \"name\": \"edit\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/javax.servlet/jsp-api/2.0/src/test/java/javax_servlet/jsp_api/SimpleTagSupportTest.java\", \"edits\": [{\"oldText\": \"    @Test\\n    void findsSimpleTagAncestorByConcreteClass() {\\n        SimpleTagSupport ancestor = new SimpleTagSupport();\\n        SimpleTagSupport child = new SimpleTagSupport();\\n        child.setParent(ancestor);\\n\\n        JspTag found = SimpleTagSupport.findAncestorWithClass(child, SimpleTagSupport.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(found).isSameAs(ancestor);\\n    }\\n\", \"newText\": \"    @Test\\n    void findsAncestorAfterLoadingTheJspTagContract() {\\n        SimpleTagSupport ancestor = new SimpleTagSupport();\\n        SimpleTagSupport child = new SimpleTagSupport();\\n        child.setParent(ancestor);\\n\\n        JspTag found = SimpleTagSupport.findAncestorWithClass(child, JspTag.class);\\n\\n        assertThat(found).isSameAs(ancestor);\\n    }\\n\"}]}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 5010, \"output\": 1982, \"cacheRead\": 15872, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 22864, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1777682687178, \"responseId\": \"resp_0ce04a3ba3fd22ec0169f548ffa24481a08461f8d87ee5e1c0\"}}\n14224:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating test structure**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to remove \\\"throws,\\\" but maybe that's not necessary. I could inspect the dynamic report, but it might not show any tests. Should I read the test result from a previous build? Adding a test to access a static method before creating instances could work by using `findAncestorWithClass`. The test call site is at line 183. But if the native image build initializes the field, that could lead to failures. Maybe I should think about creating the test class within the right package?\\n\\n**Exploring testing restrictions**\\n\\nI’m thinking about the rules that might prohibit package access. I could potentially use a subclass with an interface to exercise that interface branch. However, it seems the class$ call only executes if `class$javax$...` is null, meaning if it has a non-null static field from any prior calls, that won't be covered. To address coverage, I could create a fresh copy of the library class through a custom classloader, but that's quite complex. Using Java serialization doesn't seem to be the right fit either.\\n\\n**Inspecting dynamic access coverage**\\n\\nI need to look into the TCK runner and see if it can provide dynamic access coverage through the JaCoCo report using the call tree stack. If a class is loaded by a